|-\n| [[Courtney Barnett]]\n| ''[[Sometimes I Sit and Think, and Sometimes I Just Sit]]''\n|-\n| [[Dead Letter Circus]]\n| ''Aesthesis''\n|-\n| [[Gang of Youths]]\n| ''[[The Positions]]''\n|-\n| [[The Preatures]]\n| ''[[Blue Planet Eyes]]''\n|-\n|rowspan=\"6\" align=\"center\" | '''[[2016 in music|2016]]'''<br>{{small|[[ARIA Music Awards of 2016|(30th)]]}}\n|- style=\"background:#FAEB86\"\n| '''[[Violent Soho]]'''\n| '''''[[Waco (Violent Soho album)|Waco]]'''''\n|-\n| [[Ball Park Music]]\n| ''Every Night the Same Dream''\n|-\n| [[Boy & Bear]] \n| ''[[Limit of Love]]''\n|-\n| [[Gang of Youths]]\n| ''[[Let Me Be Clear]]''\n|-\n| [[The Living End]]\n| ''[[Shift (The Living End album)|Shift]]''\n|-\n|rowspan=\"6\" align=\"center\" | '''[[2017 in music|2017]]'''<br>{{small|[[ARIA Music Awards of 2017|(31st)]]}}\n|- style=\"background:#FAEB86\"\n| '''[[Gang of Youths]]'''\n| '''''[[Go Farther in Lightness]]''''' \n|-\n| [[Dan Sultan]]\n| ''[[Killer (Dan Sultan album)|Killer]]''\n|-\n| [[Dune Rats]]\n| ''[[The Kids Will Know It's Bullshit]]''\n|-\n| [[Polish Club (band)|Polish Club]]\n| ''Alright Already''\n|-\n| [[The Preatures]]\n| ''[[Girlhood (album)|Girlhood]]''\n|-\n|rowspan=\"6\" align=\"center\" | '''[[2018 in music|2018]]'''<br>{{small|[[ARIA Music Awards of 2018|(32nd)]]}}\n|- style=\"background:#FAEB86\"\n| '''[[Courtney Barnett]]'''\n| '''''[[Tell Me How You Really Feel]]'''''\n|-\n| [[Camp Cope]]\n| ''[[How to Socialise & Make Friends]]''\n|-\n| [[DMA's]]\n| ''[[For Now (album)|For Now]]''\n|-\n| [[Luca Brasi (band)|Luca Brasi]]\n| ''[[Stay (Luca Brasi album)|Stay]]''\n|-\n| [[Middle Kids]]\n| ''[[Lost Friends]]''\n|-\n|rowspan=\"6\" align=\"center\" | '''[[2019 in music|2019]]'''<br>{{small|[[ARIA Music Awards of 2019|(33rd)]]}}\n|- style=\"background:#FAEB86\"\n| '''[[Amyl and the Sniffers]]'''\n| '''''[[Amyl and the Sniffers (album)|Amyl and the Sniffers]]'''''\n|-\n| [[Holy Holy (Australian band)|Holy Holy]]\n| ''[[My Own Pool of Light]]''\n|-\n| [[Jimmy Barnes]]\n| ''[[My Criminal Record]]''\n|-\n| [[Midnight Oil]]\n| ''[[Armistice Day (album)|Armistice Day: Live at the Domain, Sydney]]''\n|-\n| [[Skegss]]\n| ''[[My Own Mess]]''\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.ariaawards.com.au The ARIA Awards Official website]\n\n{{ARIA music awards}}\n\n[[Category:ARIA Music Awards|H]]\n[[Category:Rock music awards|A]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toAngel (disambiguation)(link changed toThe Angels (Australian band)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ARIA_Award_for_Best_Rock_Album"}
{"title_page": "Stamatis Voulgaris", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Stamatis Voulgaris\n| image              = \n| image_size         = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = [[1774]]\n| birth_place        = [[Lefkimmi]] ([[Corfu]], [[Ionian Islands]]), [[Greece]]\n| death_date         = [[1842]]\n| death_place        = [[Lefkimmi]] ([[Corfu]], [[Ionian Islands]]), [[Greece]]\n| death_cause        = \n| resting_place      = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| residence          = \n| nationality        = [[File:Flag of Greece (1828-1978).svg|border|20px]] [[First Hellenic Republic|Greek]]<br>[[File:Flag of the Kingdom of France (1814-1830).svg|border|20px]] [[French people|French]]\n| other_names        = \n| known_for          = [[Morea expedition|Military Expedition of Morea]] (1828)<br>First urban plan of the city of [[Patras]], [[Greece]] (1829)\n| education          = [[Coll\u00e8ge des Quatre-Nations]]<br>[[Jacques-Louis David|Atelier of Jacques-Louis David]]\n| employer           = \n| occupation         = [[Military officer]]<br/>[[Urbanism|Urbanist]]<br>[[Architecture|Architect]]<br>[[Painter]]\n| title              = [[Lieutenant colonel]] of the French Army\n| salary             = \n| networth           = \n| term               = \n| predecessor        = \n| successor          = \n| party              = \n| boards             = \n| religion           = \n| spouse             = \n| children           = \n| parents            = \n| relatives          = \n| honours            = [[File:Legion_Honneur_Chevalier_ribbon.svg|45px]] [[Legion of Honour|''Knight'' of the Legion of Honour]]<br/>[[File:Ordre_Royal_et_Militaire_de_Saint-Louis_Chevalier_ribbon.svg|45px]] [[Order of Saint Louis|''Knight'' of the Order of Saint Louis]]\n| box_width          = \n}}\n'''Stamatis Voulgaris''' or '''Stamati Bulgari''' ({{lang-el|\u03a3\u03c4\u03b1\u03bc\u03ac\u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u0392\u03bf\u03cd\u03bb\u03b3\u03b1\u03c1\u03b7\u03c2}}), was a painter, an architect and the first [[urban planning|urban planner]] of modern Greece. He was born in [[Lefkimmi]] in the island of [[Corfu]], [[Greece]] in 1774, and died in 1842. He had been also granted [[French people|French]] nationality.\n\n== Life ==\n\n=== Youth ===\nStamatis Voulgaris was born in [[Lefkimmi]], on the island of [[Corfu]] in the [[Ionian Islands]], in 1774. His parents were Al\u00e9xandros Vo\u00falgaris of Aloys\u00edus and Louk\u00eda Pand\u00eds. From the age of seven, he attended school at St. Justine's monastery in Garitsa, where he learned his first letters. There, he was a classmate of [[Ioannis Kapodistrias]], the future governor of Greece. An interesting incident led him to his decision to become an urban planner. During the brief Russian-Turkish siege (1799), while in the vicinity of the San Giacomo theater in Corfu, a [[cannon]] ball fired from a Russian vessel fell beside young Voulgaris without immediately exploding. He immediately grabbed the fuse and then neutralized it, thus saving the theater and a whole French military detachment which passed nearby with heavy weapons and ammunition. French General [[Louis Fran\u00e7ois Jean Chabot]], a friend of [[Napoleon]], in order to honor his bravery, enlisted him in the French army.<ref name=\":0\">Pavlos Kyriazis, \"''Stamatis Voulgaris. The fighter, the urbanist, the man''\", ''in: Collective, First Greek Technical Scientists of the Liberation Period'', ed. Technical Chamber of Greece, Athens, 1976, p.152 \n\n\u03a0\u03b1\u03cd\u03bb\u03bf\u03c2 \u039a\u03c5\u03c1\u03b9\u03b1\u03b6\u03ae\u03c2, \u00ab\u03a3\u03c4\u03b1\u03bc\u03ac\u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u0392\u03bf\u03cd\u03bb\u03b3\u03b1\u03c1\u03b7\u03c2. \u039f \u03b1\u03b3\u03c9\u03bd\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03ae\u03c2, \u03bf \u03c0\u03bf\u03bb\u03b5\u03bf\u03b4\u03cc\u03bc\u03bf\u03c2, \u03bf \u03ac\u03bd\u03b8\u03c1\u03c9\u03c0\u03bf\u03c2\u00bb, \u03c3\u03c4\u03bf: \u03a3\u03c5\u03bb\u03bb\u03bf\u03b3\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc, \u03a0\u03c1\u03ce\u03c4\u03bf\u03b9 \u0388\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03bd\u03b5\u03c2 \u03c4\u03b5\u03c7\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03bf\u03af \u03b5\u03c0\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03ae\u03bc\u03bf\u03bd\u03b5\u03c2 \u03c0\u03b5\u03c1\u03b9\u03cc\u03b4\u03bf\u03c5 \u03b1\u03c0\u03b5\u03bb\u03b5\u03c5\u03b8\u03ad\u03c1\u03c9\u03c3\u03b7\u03c2, \u03b5\u03ba\u03b4.\u03a4\u03b5\u03c7\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc \u0395\u03c0\u03b9\u03bc\u03b5\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03c4\u03ae\u03c1\u03b9\u03bf \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03ac\u03b4\u03bf\u03c2, \u0391\u03b8\u03ae\u03bd\u03b1, 1976, \u03c3\u03b5\u03bb.152</ref> When the French left, the young man followed them to [[Paris]], where he studied [[urban planning]] in a military academy.\n\nIn 1808, he was appointed [[Lieutenant]] engineer. At the same time, he studied at the [[Coll\u00e8ge des Quatre-Nations]] (which now houses the headquarters of the [[Institut de France]]). He became an engineer geographer and an extraordinary designer in the service of the ministry's [[D\u00e9p\u00f4t de la Guerre]] (a depository of maps and archives). He participated in several military missions, notably between 1810 and 1814, as an employee at the General Staff of the governor of the [[Ionian Islands]], General [[Fran\u00e7ois-Xavier Donzelot]]. He was arrested by the English and imprisoned in [[Malta]] in 1814. When he was released, he undertook a new special mission in [[Epirus]] and [[Albania]], then was recalled to France to fight at the [[battle of Waterloo]] on 18 June 1815. After [[Napoleon]]'s defeat, he was removed from the army, then was reinstated and raised to the rank of [[Captain (armed forces)|Captain of the General Staff]]. On 30 January 1817, he was officially naturalized [[French people|French]] by order of [[Louis XVIII of France|King Louis XVIII]].<ref>(N\u00ba 1753) ''ORDONNANCE DU ROI qui accorde des Lettres de d\u00e9claration de naturalit\u00e9 au Sr. Stamati Bulgari, capitaine d'infanterie, dessinateur extraordinaire au d\u00e9p\u00f4t g\u00e9n\u00e9ral de la guerre, n\u00e9 \u00e0 Corfou, \u00eeles ioniennes, le 17 mai 1777'' (Paris, 30 Janvier 1817), p.147, in [[Bulletin des lois]], Partie principale, \u00c9diteur Imprimerie nationale, 1817.</ref>\n\n=== Barbizon School ===\n[[File:Portrait du peintre Stamati Bulgari, assis, devant son chevalet - Jean-Baptiste Camille Corot.jpg|left|thumb|300x300px|Portrait of Stamati Bulgari, seated in front of his easel (by [[Jean-Baptiste-Camille Corot|Camille Corot]] who wrotes down: \"''Stamati Bulgari in rage with reason''\")]]\nVoulgaris followed several painting courses in parallel with his studies,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kapodistrias.info/voulgaris-stamatis/185-voulgaris-stamatis|title=\u0392\u03bf\u03cd\u03bb\u03b3\u03b1\u03c1\u03b7\u03c2 \u03a3\u03c4\u03b1\u03bc\u03ac\u03c4\u03b7\u03c2|publication-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304192142/http://www.kapodistrias.info/voulgaris-stamatis/185-voulgaris-stamatis|archive-date=2016-03-04|access-date=2011-12-07}}</ref> in particular in the atelier of the renown painter [[Jacques-Louis David]].<ref name=\":0\" /> He then became part, with his fellow student, the famous painter [[Jean-Baptiste-Camille Corot|Jean-Baptiste Camille Corot]], of the first members of a whole new generation of young [[Neoclassicism|neo-classical]] painters from the 1820s, in David's suite, later called the [[Barbizon school|School of Barbizon]].<ref>David C. Thomson, ''[[iarchive:gri_33125008541878|The Barbizon School of Painters]]'', Londres, Chapman & Hall, 1891, r\u00e9\u00e9dit\u00e9 en 1902.</ref><ref>Chantal Georgel (dir.), ''La For\u00eat de Fontainebleau, un atelier grandeur nature'', catalogue de l'exposition du Mus\u00e9e d'Orsay (6 mars au 13 mai 2007), RMN, 2007. {{ISBN|978-2711852888}}</ref> This colony of [[Landscape painting|landscape artists]] (called the \"open airists\"), grouping painters such as [[Charles-Fran\u00e7ois Daubigny]], [[Th\u00e9odore Rousseau]], [[Jean-Fran\u00e7ois Millet]] or [[Gustave Courbet]], were coming together a few kilometers from Paris to work in the [[forest of Fontainebleau]] which was for them a source of inspiration.\n\nVoulgaris and Corot thus lived together in the village of [[Chailly-en-Bi\u00e8re]] from July 1821. Corot drew several portraits of Voulgaris, \"''in his bed''\" or \"''sitting in front of his easel''\" (he wrote at the bottom of the latter with a graphite stylus: \"''Stamati Bulgari in rage with reason''\"). Voulgaris also painted in 1821, in his ''[https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k6270082g Souvenirs]'' (published in 1835),<ref name=\":12\">Stamatis Voulgaris, ''[https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k6270082g Souvenirs de Stamati Bulgari, Chef de bataillon au Corps Royal d'\u00c9tat-major, en retraite]'', (Gallica - BnF), A. Pihan de La Forest (Paris), 1835.</ref> a literary painting of this forest of Fontainebleau which used to inspire him with a \"''meditative and religious feeling''\". This description is considered to be the very first known of this colony of artists.<ref>Pascal Ory, ''Dictionnaire des \u00e9trangers qui ont fait la France'', Groupe Robert Laffont, 17 Octobre 2013. {{ISBN|2221140168}}, 9782221140161</ref>\n\n=== Spain expedition and travel to the Antilles ===\nIn 1823 he fought in the 3rd Corps of the Pyrenees Army during the [[Hundred Thousand Sons of Saint Louis|Spanish military expedition]] led by France against the Spanish liberals to restore [[Ferdinand VII of Spain|King Ferdinand VII of Spain]] to his throne. On the occasion of this campaign, he wrote two chapters in his ''[https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k6270082g Souvenirs]'' from the [[Alhambra|Alhambra Palace]] in [[Granada]].<ref name=\":12\" /> In December 1825, he requested to be attached to the staff of Lieutenant-General Henri Baudrand in order to accompany him for an inspection of the engineering service in [[French Guiana]], in [[Barbados]] and in [[Martinique]], where he met again General [[Fran\u00e7ois-Xavier Donzelot|Donzelot]] (the former governor of the Ionian Islands), now governor of the island. Voulgaris twice suffered from tropical [[fever]]. He returned to France in August 1826 and devoted a chapter of his ''[https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k6270082g Souvenirs]'' to this journey.<ref name=\":12\" /><ref name=\":1\">Pavlos Kyriazis, \"''Stamatis Voulgaris. The fighter, the urbanist, the man''\", ''in: Collective, First Greek Technical Scientists of the Liberation Period'', ed. Technical Chamber of Greece, Athens, 1976, p.156\n\n\u03a0\u03b1\u03cd\u03bb\u03bf\u03c2 \u039a\u03c5\u03c1\u03b9\u03b1\u03b6\u03ae\u03c2, \u00ab\u03a3\u03c4\u03b1\u03bc\u03ac\u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u0392\u03bf\u03cd\u03bb\u03b3\u03b1\u03c1\u03b7\u03c2. \u039f \u03b1\u03b3\u03c9\u03bd\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03ae\u03c2, \u03bf \u03c0\u03bf\u03bb\u03b5\u03bf\u03b4\u03cc\u03bc\u03bf\u03c2, \u03bf \u03ac\u03bd\u03b8\u03c1\u03c9\u03c0\u03bf\u03c2\u00bb, \u03c3\u03c4\u03bf: \u03a3\u03c5\u03bb\u03bb\u03bf\u03b3\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc, \u03a0\u03c1\u03ce\u03c4\u03bf\u03b9 \u0388\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03bd\u03b5\u03c2 \u03c4\u03b5\u03c7\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03bf\u03af \u03b5\u03c0\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03ae\u03bc\u03bf\u03bd\u03b5\u03c2 \u03c0\u03b5\u03c1\u03b9\u03cc\u03b4\u03bf\u03c5 \u03b1\u03c0\u03b5\u03bb\u03b5\u03c5\u03b8\u03ad\u03c1\u03c9\u03c3\u03b7\u03c2, \u03b5\u03ba\u03b4.\u03a4\u03b5\u03c7\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc \u0395\u03c0\u03b9\u03bc\u03b5\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03c4\u03ae\u03c1\u03b9\u03bf \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03ac\u03b4\u03bf\u03c2, \u0391\u03b8\u03ae\u03bd\u03b1, 1976, \u03c3\u03b5\u03bb.156</ref>\n\n=== Morea expedition and urban planning in Greece ===\n[[File:Entrevue du g\u00e9n\u00e9ral Maison et d'Ibrahim Pacha, \u00e0 Navarin, septembre 1828 (d\u00e9tail).jpg|thumb|300x300px|General Maison, commander of the [[Morea expedition|French expedition of Morea]], meeting Ibrahim Pasha at Navarino in 1828 (by Jean-Charles Langlois)]]\nSince 1821, the [[Greek War of Independence]] was raging in Greece, which had not left Voulgaris indifferent: in 1825 he wrote in his ''[https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k6270082g Souvenirs]'': \"''Grecs, aux armes! aux armes!''\",<ref name=\":12\" /> after learning of [[Lord Byron]]'s death at [[Missolonghi]]. In October 1827, the first governor of independent Greece [[Ioannis Kapodistrias]] went to Paris to ask the French government for advisers and French army officers to organise the army of the [[First Hellenic Republic|new Greek state]]. On the recommendation of the French Ministry of War, the Captain of the General Staff of the French army, Stamatis Voulgaris, and three other officers (the Captains of the artillery [[Jean Henri Pierre Augustin Pauzi\u00e9|Jean-Henri-Pierre-Augustin Pauzi\u00e9]], of the [[Topography|topographic]] service [[Pierre Peytier]], and of the engineers [[Auguste Th\u00e9odore Garnot|Auguste-Th\u00e9odore Garnot]]) were sent to Greece in 1828 to train young Greek military engineers.<ref name=\":14\">Michel Sivignon, Universit\u00e9 Paris X - Nanterre, ''[https://pergamos.lib.uoa.gr/uoa/dl/object/1043071 Les enseignements de la carte de Gr\u00e8ce \u00e0 l\u2019\u00e9chelle de 1/200.000 (publi\u00e9e en 1852)]'' (Pergamos - Digital Library of the University of Athens (UoA)). Communication presented in the seminar of Gythion-Areopolis Lakonias \u00ab ''Voyageurs et exp\u00e9ditions scientifiques: t\u00e9moignages sur l'espace et la soci\u00e9t\u00e9 de Mani'' \u00bb, 4-7 nov 1993 and published in \u00ab ''Mani. T\u00e9moignages sur l\u2019espace et la soci\u00e9t\u00e9. Voyageurs et exp\u00e9ditions scientifiques (15\u00b0-19\u00b0 si\u00e8cle)'' \u00bb, Athens, Institut d\u2019\u00c9tudes N\u00e9o-hell\u00e9niques, 1996, p. 435-445.</ref> They were all four attached to the General Staff of [[Nicolas Joseph Maison|General Maison]], commander-in-chief of the [[Morea expedition|Morea military expedition]], whose mission was to liberate the Peloponnese from the Turkish-Egyptian occupation troops of [[Ibrahim Pasha of Egypt|Ibrahim Pasha]]. The artillery Captain Pauzi\u00e9 founded the Artillery School (\u03a3\u03c7o\u03bb\u03ae \u03a0\u03c5\u03c1o\u03b2o\u03bb\u03b9\u03bao\u03cd) and then the [[Hellenic Military Academy|Central Military Academy of the Evelpides]] (\u039a\u03b5\u03bd\u03c4\u03c1\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae \u03a3\u03c4\u03c1\u03b1\u03c4\u03b9\u03c9\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae \u03a3\u03c7\u03bf\u03bb\u03ae \u0395\u03c5\u03b5\u03bb\u03c0\u03af\u03b4\u03c9\u03bd) in 1828 on the French model of the [[\u00c9cole Polytechnique]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Andreas Kastanis|first=|date=May 2003|title=The teaching of mathematics in the Greek military academy during the first years of its foundation (1828\u20131834)|url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S031508600200023X#BIB071|journal=Historia Mathematica|volume=30|issue=2|pages=123-139|doi=10.1016/s0315-0860(02)00023-x|issn=0315-0860|via=}}</ref> Captain Peytier drew the [[:File:Map of Greece - Peytier Eug\u00e8ne - 1832.jpg|map of the Peloponnese]]. \n\nPresident Kapodistrias having appreciated the expertise of Voulgaris, the two men met first in Italy in [[Ancona]], and then embarked together aboard the frigate of the Royal Navy [[HMS Warspite (1807)|''HMS'' ''Warspite'']] for [[Nafplio]] in Greece, where they arrived on 7 January 1828 (Kapodistrias was caming to take over the governance of the country). The President asked Voulgaris to conduct a study on the search for a suitable location in the city to build a colony for war refugees there. Allocation of other urban plans followed, such as the urban planning of the cities of [[Nafplio]] (historic center and suburb of Pr\u00f3noia), [[Tripoli, Greece|Tripoli]] and [[Argos]], in collaboration with Captain Garnot.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":15\">Jacques Mangeart, ''[https://books.google.gr/books?id=OixCAAAAcAAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false Souvenirs de la Mor\u00e9e: recueillis pendant le s\u00e9jour des Fran\u00e7ais dans le Pelopon\u00e8se]'', Igonette; Paris, 1830.</ref>\n[[File:Map Patras Stamatis Voulgaris 1829.jpg|left|thumb|350x350px|The original first urban plan of [[Patras]], drawn up in 1829 by Stamatis Voulgaris and Auguste-Th\u00e9odore Garnot, Captains of the Morea expedition]]\nYet, the most important urban planning mission of Voulgaris was the planning of the city of [[Patras]] in 1829, order by the President.<ref name=\":12\" /> He arrived there on December 5, 1828 accompanied by Captain Auguste-Th\u00e9odore Garnot.<ref name=\":15\" /> The Turkish-Egyptian troops of [[Ibrahim Pasha of Egypt|Ibrahim Pasha]] had left only ruins in Patras. They had destroyed the houses, burned the gardens, uprooted all the trees and demolished the ramparts of the city fortress.<ref name=\":15\" /> Voulgaris specifically proposed to erect the modern city on the seaside, which was then a freer and more extensive area. The city, with a geometric composition, took the form of a large parallelogram bordering the coastal area and of a second ending at the periphery of the old town. Seventeen vertical and wide uphill streets intersected, at right angles, eight other horizontal streets, thus dividing the city into a hundred large blocks of buildings.<ref name=\":2\">Pavlos Kyriazis, \"''Stamatis Voulgaris. The fighter, the urbanist, the man''\", ''in: Collective, First Greek Technical Scientists of the Liberation Period'', ed. Technical Chamber of Greece, Athens, 1976, p.158\n\n\u03a0\u03b1\u03cd\u03bb\u03bf\u03c2 \u039a\u03c5\u03c1\u03b9\u03b1\u03b6\u03ae\u03c2, \u00ab\u03a3\u03c4\u03b1\u03bc\u03ac\u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u0392\u03bf\u03cd\u03bb\u03b3\u03b1\u03c1\u03b7\u03c2. \u039f \u03b1\u03b3\u03c9\u03bd\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03ae\u03c2, \u03bf \u03c0\u03bf\u03bb\u03b5\u03bf\u03b4\u03cc\u03bc\u03bf\u03c2, \u03bf \u03ac\u03bd\u03b8\u03c1\u03c9\u03c0\u03bf\u03c2\u00bb, \u03c3\u03c4\u03bf: \u03a3\u03c5\u03bb\u03bb\u03bf\u03b3\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc, \u03a0\u03c1\u03ce\u03c4\u03bf\u03b9 \u0388\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03bd\u03b5\u03c2 \u03c4\u03b5\u03c7\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03bf\u03af \u03b5\u03c0\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03ae\u03bc\u03bf\u03bd\u03b5\u03c2 \u03c0\u03b5\u03c1\u03b9\u03cc\u03b4\u03bf\u03c5 \u03b1\u03c0\u03b5\u03bb\u03b5\u03c5\u03b8\u03ad\u03c1\u03c9\u03c3\u03b7\u03c2, \u03b5\u03ba\u03b4.\u03a4\u03b5\u03c7\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc \u0395\u03c0\u03b9\u03bc\u03b5\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03c4\u03ae\u03c1\u03b9\u03bf \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03ac\u03b4\u03bf\u03c2, \u0391\u03b8\u03ae\u03bd\u03b1, 1976, \u03c3\u03b5\u03bb.158</ref> He also planned to build nine symmetrical public squares, quays, vast and long boulevards or avenues bordered by trees and perfectly ventilated, fountains, arcades, green areas round the Castle and three main doors which will open on the roads of Gastouni, Kalavrita and Corinth.<ref name=\":15\" /> Voulgaris also wanted to cover himself, on his emoluments, the financial costs for tree planting in Patras.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nHowever, the original plan was not fully implemented, because on the one hand the [[kodjabashis]] (notables and primates) and the local property owners put the governor Kapodistrias under pressure to prevent any change, and on the other hand state finances were not sufficient to achieve the visionary plan of Voulgaris: in 1830, the 5 symmetrical [[Town square|squares]] he had designed in the parallelogram bordering the coastal area were reduced to 2 only, including the central square of ''Democracy'' (currently [[Georgiou I Square|King Georgiou I Square]]) and square of ''Concord'' (currently [[Olgas Square|Queen Olga Square]]). [[File:\u03a0\u03ac\u03c4\u03c1\u03b1,\u03c4\u03bf \u03c0\u03c1\u03ce\u03c4\u03bf \u03c3\u03c7\u03ad\u03b4\u03b9\u03bf \u03c0\u03cc\u03bb\u03b7\u03c2 (1829).jpg|thumb|250x250px|Modified urban plan of [[Patras]] after 1830 (with the reduced of number of squares)|alt=]]After handing over the city's plans to Governor Kapod\u00edstrias, Voulgaris joined the troops of the regular Greek army, then commanded by the governor's brother, [[Augustinos Kapodistrias]], chief of the expedition of mainland Greece. Captain Voulgaris was responsible in particular for drawing the plan of the siege of [[Nafpaktos|Lepanto (Nafpaktos)]] and the direction of its works.<ref name=\":12\" /> In April 1829 the siege fell and the city was taken over from the Turks. Voulgaris indicated in his ''[https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k6270082g Souvenirs]'' that \"''this important conquest brought that of [[Missolonghi]] (in May), where ended, with this Greek expedition, my military career.''\"<ref name=\":12\" />\n\n=== Last years in Corfu ===\nIn August 1830, Voulgaris, sick, returned to France and was raised in 1831 to the rank of [[Lieutenant colonel|Chief of Battalion]]. In 1838, he retired to his native land of [[Corfu]], in the village of Potam\u00f3s near [[Lefkimmi]], where he died in 1842. In his will, he left money to various friends and relatives, and, moreover, to the French Consulate to distribute to the French indigents of Corfu.<ref>(N\u00ba 19,587) ''ORDONNANCE DU ROI (contre-sign\u00e9e par le garde des sceaux, ministre de la justice et des cultes) qui autorise le ministre des affaires \u00e9trang\u00e8res \u00e0 accepter la disposition faite par M. Stamati Bulgari, chef de bataillon en retraite, dans son testament, en date du 12 juillet 1842, au profit des Fran\u00e7ais indigents qui arriveraient \u00e0 Corfou ; pour, ladite disposition, \u00eatre ex\u00e9cut\u00e9e conform\u00e9ment aux intentions du testateur. (Paris, 19 Mai 1845.)'', p.896, in [[Bulletin des lois de la R\u00e9publique Fran\u00e7aise]], Volume 27, \u00c9diteur Imprimerie nationale des lois, 1845.</ref> He was:\n\n* [[File:Legion_Honneur_Chevalier_ribbon.svg|60px]] [[Legion of Honour|''Knight'' of the Legion of Honour]].\n* [[File:Ordre_Royal_et_Militaire_de_Saint-Louis_Chevalier_ribbon.svg|60px]] [[Order of Saint Louis|''Knight'' of the Order of Saint-Louis]].\n\n== Publications ==\n\n* Stamatis Voulgaris, ''[https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k318451c Examen moral des principaux tableaux de la galerie du Luxembourg en 1818, et consid\u00e9rations sur l'\u00e9tat actuel de la peinture en France, par M. Stamati Bulgari]'', (Gallica - BnF), Paris, 1827.\n* Stamatis Voulgaris, ''Notice sur le comte Jean Capodistrias, Pr\u00e9sident de la Gr\u00e8ce, suivie d'un extrait de sa correspondance'' ; ''par Stamati Bulgari, Chef de bataillon au Corps Royal d\u2019\u00c9tat-major'', Delaunay, Paris, 1832.\n* Stamatis Voulgaris, ''[https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k6270082g Souvenirs de Stamati Bulgari, Chef de bataillon au Corps Royal d'\u00c9tat-major, en retraite]'', (Gallica - BnF), A. Pihan de La Forest, Paris, 1835.\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{Greek War of Independence}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Voulgaris, Stamatis}}\n[[Category:Greek urban planners]]\n[[Category:Greek architects]]\n[[Category:1779 births]]\n[[Category:People from Corfu]]\n[[Category:Ioannis Kapodistrias]]\n[[Category:History of Patras]]\n[[Category:1842 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Stamatis Voulgaris\n| image              = \n| image_size         = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = [[1774]]\n| birth_place        = [[Lefkimmi]] ([[Corfu]], [[Ionian Islands]]), [[Greece]]\n| death_date         = [[1842]]\n| death_place        = [[Lefkimmi]] ([[Corfu]], [[Ionian Islands]]), [[Greece]]\n| death_cause        = \n| resting_place      = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| residence          = \n| nationality        = [[File:Flag of Greece (1828-1978).svg|border|20px]] [[First Hellenic Republic|Greek]]<br>[[File:Flag of the Kingdom of France (1814-1830).svg|border|20px]] [[French people|French]]\n| other_names        = \n| known_for          = [[Morea expedition|Military Expedition of Morea]] (1828)<br>First urban plan of the city of [[Patras]], [[Greece]] (1829)\n| education          = [[Coll\u00e8ge des Quatre-Nations]]<br>[[Jacques-Louis David|Atelier of Jacques-Louis David]]\n| employer           = \n| occupation         = [[Military officer]]<br/>[[Urbanism|Urbanist]]<br>[[Architecture|Architect]]<br>[[Painter]]\n| title              = [[Lieutenant colonel]] of the French Army\n| salary             = \n| networth           = \n| term               = \n| predecessor        = \n| successor          = \n| party              = \n| boards             = \n| religion           = \n| spouse             = \n| children           = \n| parents            = \n| relatives          = \n| honours            = [[File:Legion_Honneur_Chevalier_ribbon.svg|45px]] [[Legion of Honour|''Knight'' of the Legion of Honour]]<br/>[[File:Ordre_Royal_et_Militaire_de_Saint-Louis_Chevalier_ribbon.svg|45px]] [[Order of Saint Louis|''Knight'' of the Order of Saint Louis]]\n| box_width          = \n}}\n'''Stamatis Voulgaris''' or '''Stamati Bulgari''' ({{lang-el|\u03a3\u03c4\u03b1\u03bc\u03ac\u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u0392\u03bf\u03cd\u03bb\u03b3\u03b1\u03c1\u03b7\u03c2}}), was a painter, an architect and the first [[urban planning|urban planner]] of modern Greece. He was born in [[Lefkimmi]] in the island of [[Corfu]], [[Greece]] in 1774, and died in 1842. He had been also granted [[French people|French]] nationality.\n\n== Life ==\n\n=== Youth ===\nStamatis Voulgaris was born in [[Lefkimmi]], on the island of [[Corfu]] in the [[Ionian Islands]], in 1774. His parents were Al\u00e9xandros Vo\u00falgaris of Aloys\u00edus and Louk\u00eda Pand\u00eds. From the age of seven, he attended school at St. Justine's monastery in Garitsa, where he learned his first letters. There, he was a classmate of [[Ioannis Kapodistrias]], the future governor of Greece. An interesting incident led him to his decision to become an urban planner. During the brief Russian-Turkish siege (1799), while in the vicinity of the San Giacomo theater in Corfu, a [[cannon]] ball fired from a Russian vessel fell beside young Voulgaris without immediately exploding. He immediately grabbed the fuse and then neutralized it, thus saving the theater and a whole French military detachment which passed nearby with heavy weapons and ammunition. French General [[Louis Fran\u00e7ois Jean Chabot]], a friend of [[Napoleon]], in order to honor his bravery, enlisted him in the French army.<ref name=\":0\">Pavlos Kyriazis, \"''Stamatis Voulgaris. The fighter, the urbanist, the man''\", ''in: Collective, First Greek Technical Scientists of the Liberation Period'', ed. Technical Chamber of Greece, Athens, 1976, p.152 \n\n\u03a0\u03b1\u03cd\u03bb\u03bf\u03c2 \u039a\u03c5\u03c1\u03b9\u03b1\u03b6\u03ae\u03c2, \u00ab\u03a3\u03c4\u03b1\u03bc\u03ac\u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u0392\u03bf\u03cd\u03bb\u03b3\u03b1\u03c1\u03b7\u03c2. \u039f \u03b1\u03b3\u03c9\u03bd\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03ae\u03c2, \u03bf \u03c0\u03bf\u03bb\u03b5\u03bf\u03b4\u03cc\u03bc\u03bf\u03c2, \u03bf \u03ac\u03bd\u03b8\u03c1\u03c9\u03c0\u03bf\u03c2\u00bb, \u03c3\u03c4\u03bf: \u03a3\u03c5\u03bb\u03bb\u03bf\u03b3\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc, \u03a0\u03c1\u03ce\u03c4\u03bf\u03b9 \u0388\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03bd\u03b5\u03c2 \u03c4\u03b5\u03c7\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03bf\u03af \u03b5\u03c0\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03ae\u03bc\u03bf\u03bd\u03b5\u03c2 \u03c0\u03b5\u03c1\u03b9\u03cc\u03b4\u03bf\u03c5 \u03b1\u03c0\u03b5\u03bb\u03b5\u03c5\u03b8\u03ad\u03c1\u03c9\u03c3\u03b7\u03c2, \u03b5\u03ba\u03b4.\u03a4\u03b5\u03c7\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc \u0395\u03c0\u03b9\u03bc\u03b5\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03c4\u03ae\u03c1\u03b9\u03bf \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03ac\u03b4\u03bf\u03c2, \u0391\u03b8\u03ae\u03bd\u03b1, 1976, \u03c3\u03b5\u03bb.152</ref> When the French left, the young man followed them to [[Paris]], where he studied [[urban planning]] in a military academy.\n\nIn 1808, he was appointed [[Lieutenant]] engineer. At the same time, he studied at the [[Coll\u00e8ge des Quatre-Nations]] (which now houses the headquarters of the [[Institut de France]]). He became an engineer geographer and an extraordinary designer in the service of the ministry's [[D\u00e9p\u00f4t de la Guerre]] (a depository of maps and archives). He participated in several military missions, notably between 1810 and 1814, as an employee at the General Staff of the governor of the [[Ionian Islands]], General [[Fran\u00e7ois-Xavier Donzelot]]. He was arrested by the English and imprisoned in [[Malta]] in 1814. When he was released, he undertook a new special mission in [[Epirus]] and [[Albania]], then was recalled to France to fight at the [[battle of Waterloo]] on 18 June 1815. After [[Napoleon]]'s defeat, he was removed from the army, then was reinstated and raised to the rank of [[Captain (armed forces)|Captain of the General Staff]]. On 30 January 1817, he was officially naturalized [[French people|French]] by order of [[Louis XVIII of France|King Louis XVIII]].<ref>(N\u00ba 1753) ''ORDONNANCE DU ROI qui accorde des Lettres de d\u00e9claration de naturalit\u00e9 au Sr. Stamati Bulgari, capitaine d'infanterie, dessinateur extraordinaire au d\u00e9p\u00f4t g\u00e9n\u00e9ral de la guerre, n\u00e9 \u00e0 Corfou, \u00eeles ioniennes, le 17 mai 1777'' (Paris, 30 Janvier 1817), p.147, in [[Bulletin des lois]], Partie principale, \u00c9diteur Imprimerie nationale, 1817.</ref>\n\n=== Barbizon School ===\n[[File:Portrait du peintre Stamati Bulgari, assis, devant son chevalet - Jean-Baptiste Camille Corot.jpg|left|thumb|300x300px|Portrait of Stamati Bulgari, seated in front of his easel (by [[Jean-Baptiste-Camille Corot|Camille Corot]] who wrotes down: \"''Stamati Bulgari in rage with reason''\")]]\nVoulgaris followed several painting courses in parallel with his studies,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kapodistrias.info/voulgaris-stamatis/185-voulgaris-stamatis|title=\u0392\u03bf\u03cd\u03bb\u03b3\u03b1\u03c1\u03b7\u03c2 \u03a3\u03c4\u03b1\u03bc\u03ac\u03c4\u03b7\u03c2|publication-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304192142/http://www.kapodistrias.info/voulgaris-stamatis/185-voulgaris-stamatis|archive-date=2016-03-04|access-date=2011-12-07}}</ref> in particular in the atelier of the renown painter [[Jacques-Louis David]].<ref name=\":0\" /> He then became part, with his fellow student, the famous painter [[Jean-Baptiste-Camille Corot|Jean-Baptiste Camille Corot]], of the first members of a whole new generation of young [[Neoclassicism|neo-classical]] painters from the 1820s, in David's suite, later called the [[Barbizon school|School of Barbizon]].<ref>David C. Thomson, ''[[iarchive:gri_33125008541878|The Barbizon School of Painters]]'', Londres, Chapman & Hall, 1891, r\u00e9\u00e9dit\u00e9 en 1902.</ref><ref>Chantal Georgel (dir.), ''La For\u00eat de Fontainebleau, un atelier grandeur nature'', catalogue de l'exposition du Mus\u00e9e d'Orsay (6 mars au 13 mai 2007), RMN, 2007. {{ISBN|978-2711852888}}</ref> This colony of [[Landscape painting|landscape artists]] (called the \"open airists\"), grouping painters such as [[Charles-Fran\u00e7ois Daubigny]], [[Th\u00e9odore Rousseau]], [[Jean-Fran\u00e7ois Millet]] or [[Gustave Courbet]], were coming together a few kilometers from Paris to work in the [[forest of Fontainebleau]] which was for them a source of inspiration.\n\nVoulgaris and Corot thus lived together in the village of [[Chailly-en-Bi\u00e8re]] from July 1821. Corot drew several portraits of Voulgaris, \"''in his bed''\" or \"''sitting in front of his easel''\" (he wrote at the bottom of the latter with a graphite stylus: \"''Stamati Bulgari in rage with reason''\"). Voulgaris also painted in 1821, in his ''[https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k6270082g Souvenirs]'' (published in 1835),<ref name=\":12\">Stamatis Voulgaris, ''[https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k6270082g Souvenirs de Stamati Bulgari, Chef de bataillon au Corps Royal d'\u00c9tat-major, en retraite]'', (Gallica - BnF), A. Pihan de La Forest (Paris), 1835.</ref> a literary painting of this forest of Fontainebleau which used to inspire him with a \"''meditative and religious feeling''\". This description is considered to be the very first known of this colony of artists.<ref>Pascal Ory, ''Dictionnaire des \u00e9trangers qui ont fait la France'', Groupe Robert Laffont, 17 Octobre 2013. {{ISBN|2221140168}}, 9782221140161</ref>\n\n=== Spain expedition and travel to the Antilles ===\nIn 1823 he fought in the 3rd Corps of the Pyrenees Army during the [[Hundred Thousand Sons of Saint Louis|Spanish military expedition]] led by France against the Spanish liberals to restore [[Ferdinand VII of Spain|King Ferdinand VII of Spain]] to his throne. On the occasion of this campaign, he wrote two chapters in his ''[https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k6270082g Souvenirs]'' from the [[Alhambra|Alhambra Palace]] in [[Granada]].<ref name=\":12\" /> In December 1825, he requested to be attached to the staff of Lieutenant-General Henri Baudrand in order to accompany him for an inspection of the engineering service in [[French Guiana]], in [[Barbados]] and in [[Martinique]], where he met again General [[Fran\u00e7ois-Xavier Donzelot|Donzelot]] (the former governor of the Ionian Islands), now governor of the island. Voulgaris twice suffered from tropical [[fever]]. He returned to France in August 1826 and devoted a chapter of his ''[https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k6270082g Souvenirs]'' to this journey.<ref name=\":12\" /><ref name=\":1\">Pavlos Kyriazis, \"''Stamatis Voulgaris. The fighter, the urbanist, the man''\", ''in: Collective, First Greek Technical Scientists of the Liberation Period'', ed. Technical Chamber of Greece, Athens, 1976, p.156\n\n\u03a0\u03b1\u03cd\u03bb\u03bf\u03c2 \u039a\u03c5\u03c1\u03b9\u03b1\u03b6\u03ae\u03c2, \u00ab\u03a3\u03c4\u03b1\u03bc\u03ac\u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u0392\u03bf\u03cd\u03bb\u03b3\u03b1\u03c1\u03b7\u03c2. \u039f \u03b1\u03b3\u03c9\u03bd\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03ae\u03c2, \u03bf \u03c0\u03bf\u03bb\u03b5\u03bf\u03b4\u03cc\u03bc\u03bf\u03c2, \u03bf \u03ac\u03bd\u03b8\u03c1\u03c9\u03c0\u03bf\u03c2\u00bb, \u03c3\u03c4\u03bf: \u03a3\u03c5\u03bb\u03bb\u03bf\u03b3\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc, \u03a0\u03c1\u03ce\u03c4\u03bf\u03b9 \u0388\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03bd\u03b5\u03c2 \u03c4\u03b5\u03c7\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03bf\u03af \u03b5\u03c0\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03ae\u03bc\u03bf\u03bd\u03b5\u03c2 \u03c0\u03b5\u03c1\u03b9\u03cc\u03b4\u03bf\u03c5 \u03b1\u03c0\u03b5\u03bb\u03b5\u03c5\u03b8\u03ad\u03c1\u03c9\u03c3\u03b7\u03c2, \u03b5\u03ba\u03b4.\u03a4\u03b5\u03c7\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc \u0395\u03c0\u03b9\u03bc\u03b5\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03c4\u03ae\u03c1\u03b9\u03bf \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03ac\u03b4\u03bf\u03c2, \u0391\u03b8\u03ae\u03bd\u03b1, 1976, \u03c3\u03b5\u03bb.156</ref>\n\n=== Morea expedition and urban planning in Greece ===\n[[File:Entrevue du g\u00e9n\u00e9ral Maison et d'Ibrahim Pacha, \u00e0 Navarin, septembre 1828 (d\u00e9tail).jpg|thumb|300x300px|General Maison, commander of the [[Morea expedition|French expedition of Morea]], meeting Ibrahim Pasha at Navarino in 1828 (by Jean-Charles Langlois)]]\nSince 1821, the [[Greek War of Independence]] was raging in Greece, which had not left Voulgaris indifferent: in 1825 he wrote in his ''[https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k6270082g Souvenirs]'': \"''Grecs, aux armes! aux armes!''\",<ref name=\":12\" /> after learning of [[Lord Byron]]'s death at [[Missolonghi]]. In October 1827, the first governor of independent Greece [[Ioannis Kapodistrias]] went to Paris to ask the French government for advisers and French army officers to organise the army of the [[First Hellenic Republic|new Greek state]]. On the recommendation of the French Ministry of War, the Captain of the General Staff of the French army, Stamatis Voulgaris, and three other officers (the Captains of the artillery [[Jean Henri Pierre Augustin Pauzi\u00e9|Jean-Henri-Pierre-Augustin Pauzi\u00e9]], of the [[Topography|topographic]] service [[Pierre Peytier]], and of the engineers [[Auguste Th\u00e9odore Garnot|Auguste-Th\u00e9odore Garnot]]) were sent to Greece in 1828 to train young Greek military engineers.<ref name=\":14\">Michel Sivignon, Universit\u00e9 Paris X - Nanterre, ''[https://pergamos.lib.uoa.gr/uoa/dl/object/1043071 Les enseignements de la carte de Gr\u00e8ce \u00e0 l\u2019\u00e9chelle de 1/200.000 (publi\u00e9e en 1852)]'' (Pergamos - Digital Library of the University of Athens (UoA)). Communication presented in the seminar of Gythion-Areopolis Lakonias \u00ab ''Voyageurs et exp\u00e9ditions scientifiques: t\u00e9moignages sur l'espace et la soci\u00e9t\u00e9 de Mani'' \u00bb, 4-7 nov 1993 and published in \u00ab ''Mani. T\u00e9moignages sur l\u2019espace et la soci\u00e9t\u00e9. Voyageurs et exp\u00e9ditions scientifiques (15\u00b0-19\u00b0 si\u00e8cle)'' \u00bb, Athens, Institut d\u2019\u00c9tudes N\u00e9o-hell\u00e9niques, 1996, p. 435-445.</ref> They were all four attached to the General Staff of [[Nicolas Joseph Maison|General Maison]], commander-in-chief of the [[Morea expedition|Morea military expedition]], whose mission was to liberate the Peloponnese from the Turkish-Egyptian occupation troops of [[Ibrahim Pasha of Egypt|Ibrahim Pasha]]. The artillery Captain Pauzi\u00e9 founded the Artillery School (\u03a3\u03c7o\u03bb\u03ae \u03a0\u03c5\u03c1o\u03b2o\u03bb\u03b9\u03bao\u03cd) and then the [[Hellenic Military Academy|Central Military Academy of the Evelpides]] (\u039a\u03b5\u03bd\u03c4\u03c1\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae \u03a3\u03c4\u03c1\u03b1\u03c4\u03b9\u03c9\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae \u03a3\u03c7\u03bf\u03bb\u03ae \u0395\u03c5\u03b5\u03bb\u03c0\u03af\u03b4\u03c9\u03bd) in 1828 on the French model of the [[\u00c9cole Polytechnique]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Andreas Kastanis|first=|date=May 2003|title=The teaching of mathematics in the Greek military academy during the first years of its foundation (1828\u20131834)|url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S031508600200023X#BIB071|journal=Historia Mathematica|volume=30|issue=2|pages=123-139|doi=10.1016/s0315-0860(02)00023-x|issn=0315-0860|via=}}</ref> Captain Peytier drew the [[:File:Map of Greece - Peytier Eug\u00e8ne - 1832.jpg|map of the Peloponnese]]. \n\nPresident Kapodistrias having appreciated the expertise of Voulgaris, the two men met first in Italy in [[Ancona]], and then embarked together aboard the frigate of the Royal Navy [[HMS Warspite (1807)|''HMS'' ''Warspite'']] for [[Nafplio]] in Greece, where they arrived on 7 January 1828 (Kapodistrias was caming to take over the governance of the country). The President asked Voulgaris to conduct a study on the search for a suitable location in the city to build a colony for war refugees there. Allocation of other urban plans followed, such as the urban planning of the cities of [[Nafplio]] (historic center and suburb of Pr\u00f3noia), [[Tripoli, Greece|Tripoli]] and [[Argos]], in collaboration with Captain Garnot.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":15\">Jacques Mangeart, ''[https://books.google.gr/books?id=OixCAAAAcAAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false Souvenirs de la Mor\u00e9e: recueillis pendant le s\u00e9jour des Fran\u00e7ais dans le Pelopon\u00e8se]'', Igonette; Paris, 1830.</ref>\n[[File:Map Patras Stamatis Voulgaris 1829.jpg|left|thumb|350x350px|The original first urban plan of [[Patras]], drawn up in 1829 by Stamatis Voulgaris and Auguste-Th\u00e9odore Garnot, Captains of the Morea expedition]]\nYet, the most important urban planning mission of Voulgaris was the planning of the city of [[Patras]] in 1829, order by the President.<ref name=\":12\" /> He arrived there on December 5, 1828 accompanied by Captain Auguste-Th\u00e9odore Garnot.<ref name=\":15\" /> The Turkish-Egyptian troops of [[Ibrahim Pasha of Egypt|Ibrahim Pasha]] had left only ruins in Patras. They had destroyed the houses, burned the gardens, uprooted all the trees and demolished the ramparts of the city fortress.<ref name=\":15\" /> Voulgaris specifically proposed to erect the modern city on the seaside, which was then a freer and more extensive area. The city, with a geometric composition, took the form of a large parallelogram bordering the coastal area and of a second ending at the periphery of the old town. Seventeen vertical and wide uphill streets intersected, at right angles, eight other horizontal streets, thus dividing the city into a hundred large blocks of buildings.<ref name=\":2\">Pavlos Kyriazis, \"''Stamatis Voulgaris. The fighter, the urbanist, the man''\", ''in: Collective, First Greek Technical Scientists of the Liberation Period'', ed. Technical Chamber of Greece, Athens, 1976, p.158\n\n\u03a0\u03b1\u03cd\u03bb\u03bf\u03c2 \u039a\u03c5\u03c1\u03b9\u03b1\u03b6\u03ae\u03c2, \u00ab\u03a3\u03c4\u03b1\u03bc\u03ac\u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u0392\u03bf\u03cd\u03bb\u03b3\u03b1\u03c1\u03b7\u03c2. \u039f \u03b1\u03b3\u03c9\u03bd\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03ae\u03c2, \u03bf \u03c0\u03bf\u03bb\u03b5\u03bf\u03b4\u03cc\u03bc\u03bf\u03c2, \u03bf \u03ac\u03bd\u03b8\u03c1\u03c9\u03c0\u03bf\u03c2\u00bb, \u03c3\u03c4\u03bf: \u03a3\u03c5\u03bb\u03bb\u03bf\u03b3\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc, \u03a0\u03c1\u03ce\u03c4\u03bf\u03b9 \u0388\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03bd\u03b5\u03c2 \u03c4\u03b5\u03c7\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03bf\u03af \u03b5\u03c0\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03ae\u03bc\u03bf\u03bd\u03b5\u03c2 \u03c0\u03b5\u03c1\u03b9\u03cc\u03b4\u03bf\u03c5 \u03b1\u03c0\u03b5\u03bb\u03b5\u03c5\u03b8\u03ad\u03c1\u03c9\u03c3\u03b7\u03c2, \u03b5\u03ba\u03b4.\u03a4\u03b5\u03c7\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc \u0395\u03c0\u03b9\u03bc\u03b5\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03c4\u03ae\u03c1\u03b9\u03bf \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03ac\u03b4\u03bf\u03c2, \u0391\u03b8\u03ae\u03bd\u03b1, 1976, \u03c3\u03b5\u03bb.158</ref> He also planned to build nine symmetrical public squares, quays, vast and long boulevards or avenues bordered by trees and perfectly ventilated, fountains, arcades, green areas round the Castle and three main doors which will open on the roads of Gastouni, Kalavrita and Corinth.<ref name=\":15\" /> Voulgaris also wanted to cover himself, on his emoluments, the financial costs for tree planting in Patras.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nHowever, the original plan was not fully implemented, because on the one hand the [[kodjabashis]] (notables and primates) and the local property owners put the governor Kapodistrias under pressure to prevent any change, and on the other hand state finances were not sufficient to achieve the visionary plan of Voulgaris: in 1830, the 5 symmetrical [[Town square|squares]] he had designed in the parallelogram bordering the coastal area were reduced to 2 only, including the central square of ''Democracy'' (currently [[Georgiou I Square|King Georgiou I Square]]) and square of ''Concord'' (currently [[Olgas Square|Queen Olga Square]]). [[File:\u03a0\u03ac\u03c4\u03c1\u03b1,\u03c4\u03bf \u03c0\u03c1\u03ce\u03c4\u03bf \u03c3\u03c7\u03ad\u03b4\u03b9\u03bf \u03c0\u03cc\u03bb\u03b7\u03c2 (1829).jpg|thumb|250x250px|Modified urban plan of [[Patras]] after 1830 (with the reduced of number of squares)|alt=]]After handing over the city's plans to Governor Kapod\u00edstrias, Voulgaris joined the troops of the regular Greek army, then commanded by the governor's brother, [[Augustinos Kapodistrias]], chief of the expedition of mainland Greece. Captain Voulgaris was responsible in particular for drawing the plan of the siege of [[Nafpaktos|Lepanto (Nafpaktos)]] and the direction of its works.<ref name=\":12\" /> In April 1829 the siege fell and the city was taken over from the Turks. Voulgaris indicated in his ''[https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k6270082g Souvenirs]'' that \"''this important conquest brought that of [[Missolonghi]] (in May), where ended, with this Greek expedition, my military career.''\"<ref name=\":12\" />\n\n=== Last years in Corfu ===\nIn August 1830, Voulgaris, sick, returned to France and was raised in 1831 to the rank of [[Lieutenant colonel|Chief of Battalion]]. In 1838, he retired to his native land of [[Corfu]], in the village of Potam\u00f3s near [[Lefkimmi]], where he died in 1842. In his will, he left money to various friends and relatives, and, moreover, to the French Consulate to distribute to the French indigents of Corfu.<ref>(N\u00ba 19,587) ''ORDONNANCE DU ROI (contre-sign\u00e9e par le garde des sceaux, ministre de la justice et des cultes) qui autorise le ministre des affaires \u00e9trang\u00e8res \u00e0 accepter la disposition faite par M. Stamati Bulgari, chef de bataillon en retraite, dans son testament, en date du 12 juillet 1842, au profit des Fran\u00e7ais indigents qui arriveraient \u00e0 Corfou ; pour, ladite disposition, \u00eatre ex\u00e9cut\u00e9e conform\u00e9ment aux intentions du testateur. (Paris, 19 Mai 1845.)'', p.896, in [[Bulletin des lois de la R\u00e9publique Fran\u00e7aise]], Volume 27, \u00c9diteur Imprimerie nationale des lois, 1845.</ref> He was:\n\n* [[File:Legion_Honneur_Chevalier_ribbon.svg|60px]] [[Legion of Honour|''Knight'' of the Legion of Honour]].\n* [[File:Ordre_Royal_et_Militaire_de_Saint-Louis_Chevalier_ribbon.svg|60px]] [[Order of Saint Louis|''Knight'' of the Order of Saint-Louis]].\n\n== Publications ==\n\n* Stamatis Voulgaris, ''[https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k318451c Examen moral des principaux tableaux de la galerie du Luxembourg en 1818, et consid\u00e9rations sur l'\u00e9tat actuel de la peinture en France, par M. Stamati Bulgari]'', (Gallica - BnF), Paris, 1827.\n* Stamatis Voulgaris, ''Notice sur le comte Jean Capodistrias, Pr\u00e9sident de la Gr\u00e8ce, suivie d'un extrait de sa correspondance'' ; ''par Stamati Bulgari, Chef de bataillon au Corps Royal d\u2019\u00c9tat-major'', Delaunay, Paris, 1832.\n* Stamatis Voulgaris, ''[https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k6270082g Souvenirs de Stamati Bulgari, Chef de bataillon au Corps Royal d'\u00c9tat-major, en retraite]'', (Gallica - BnF), A. Pihan de La Forest, Paris, 1835.\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{Greek War of Independence}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Voulgaris, Stamatis}}\n[[Category:Greek urban planners]]\n[[Category:Greek architects]]\n[[Category:1779 births]]\n[[Category:People from Corfu]]\n[[Category:Ioannis Kapodistrias]]\n[[Category:1842 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "Greco22", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stamatis_Voulgaris"}
